  <body>
      <p>Benzylideneanilines (Schiff bases) exhibit very interesting thermochromic and photochromic properties. Therefore, they became a topic of numerous recent publications [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B1-molbank-2012-M759">1</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B2-molbank-2012-M759">2</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B3-molbank-2012-M759">3</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B4-molbank-2012-M759">4</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B5-molbank-2012-M759">5</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B6-molbank-2012-M759">6</xref>]. Flexible long alkyl chain at the <italic>para</italic> position of <italic>N</italic>-benzylideneanilines has also been viewed as one of the important criteria for exhibition of liquid crystal phases [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B7-molbank-2012-M759">7</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B8-molbank-2012-M759">8</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B9-molbank-2012-M759">9</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B10-molbank-2012-M759">10</xref>]. Different alkyl chain length and terminal substituent can significantly influence the anisotropic properties of liquid crystals [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B7-molbank-2012-M759">7</xref>,<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B8-molbank-2012-M759">8</xref>]. Thus, we report here another new derivative containing an hexadecanoyloxy chain, 4-{[(4-chlorophenyl)imino]methyl}-3-hydroxyphenyl 4-(hexadecanoyloxy)benzoate.</p>
